</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">With the increasing popularity of assisted reproductive technology (ART), radiologists are more likely to encounter associated complications, especially in an emergency setting. These complications include ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome (OHSS), ovarian torsion, and ectopic and heterotopic pregnancy. OHSS occurs following ovulation induction or ovarian stimulation and manifests with bilateral ovarian enlargement by multiple cysts, third-spacing of fluids, and clinical findings ranging from gastrointestinal discomfort to life-threatening renal failure and coagulopathy. Enlarged hyperstimulated ovaries are at risk for torsion. Clinical symptoms are often nonspecific, and ovarian torsion should be suspected and excluded in any female patient undergoing infertility treatment who presents with severe abdominal pain. The most consistent imaging finding is asymmetric enlargement of the twisted ovary. There is also an increased risk for ectopic pregnancy following ART, with a relative increased risk for rarer and more lethal forms, including interstitial and cervical ectopic pregnancies. Heterotopic pregnancy refers to simultaneous intrauterine and ectopic pregnancies and has an incidence of 1%–3% in ART patients. Careful evaluation of the adnexa is critical in this patient population, even when an intrauterine pregnancy has been confirmed. Ultrasonography is the first-line imaging modality for the evaluation of complications of ART, although nonspecific symptoms may sometimes lead to cross-sectional imaging being performed. Familiarity with the multimodality imaging appearance of these entities will allow accurate and timely diagnosis and help avert potentially fatal consequences.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.331125011">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.331125011">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig01.jpeg" height="287" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Drawings illustrate the IVF procedure, which consists of four steps: ovarian stimulation by a combination of fertility medications (step 1), oocyte retrieval by means of transvaginal US–guided follicle aspiration (step 2), laboratory (ie, in vitro) fertilization of the oocyte and sperm (step 3), and transcervical transfer of the embryo into the uterine cavity (step 4).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig02.jpeg" height="883" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Drawing illustrates the proposed pathogenesis of OHSS. Following the administration of fertility medications, a large cohort of ovarian follicles is developed and sustained. The granulosa-lutein cells, under the influence of hCG, produce vascular endothelial growth factor <i>(VEGF)</i>, which in turn acts on endothelial cells to produce vascular permeability and accumulation of fluid in the extravascular space. (Adapted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r7" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r7">7</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig03a.jpeg" height="935" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig03b.jpeg" height="924" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig04a.jpeg" height="899" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig04b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1222" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig05.jpeg" height="879" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Hemorrhagic cyst in OHSS. Longitudinal transvaginal US image of an enlarged, hyperstimulated right ovary (calipers) shows a dominant cyst with echogenic material adhering to the cyst wall, a finding that is consistent with a retracting blood clot (a normal finding). A small amount of free fluid is seen surrounding the ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig06.jpeg" height="1280" width="1157" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> OHSS. Coronal CT scan obtained following the intravenous and oral administration of contrast material shows bilateral ovarian enlargement by multiple cysts (arrows), as well as limited perihepatic ascites (arrowhead). <i>UT</i> = uterus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig07.jpeg" height="1280" width="1107" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> OHSS in a 22-year-old woman who had undergone IVF. The patient presented with right lower quadrant pain and a serum β-hCG level of 644 mIU/mL. MR imaging was performed for clinical suspicion of appendicitis. Coronal fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows bilateral ovarian enlargement (arrows) and limited ascites (arrowhead). <i>B</i> = bladder.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig08.jpeg" height="1280" width="1109" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Thromboembolism in OHSS. Head CT scan shows acute infarction of the right middle cerebral artery. Thromboembolic events are the most feared complication of OHSS. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r13" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r13">13</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig09a.jpeg" height="978" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig09b.jpeg" height="979" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig09c.jpeg" height="1082" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig09c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig10a.jpeg" height="839" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig10b.jpeg" height="890" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig10c.jpeg" height="876" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig11.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Whirlpool sign in ovarian torsion. Power Doppler image of the right ovary shows the typical “corkscrew” appearance of a twisted vascular pedicle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig12.jpeg" height="926" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Ovarian torsion in a 32-year-old woman who had undergone IVF. The patient presented with intermittent severe abdominal pain and a serum β-hCG level of 161 mIU/mL. Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows an asymmetrically enlarged left ovary (arrow) located in the midline pelvis within the cul-de-sac, along with limited ascites (*). The uterus <i>(UT)</i> demonstrates mild leftward deviation, another secondary sign of torsion. The right ovary (not shown) was identified separately. Left ovarian torsion was confirmed at laparoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/large/125011fig13.jpeg" height="767" width="1251" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Drawing illustrates ectopic pregnancy locations in ART patients versus patients who conceive naturally. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r36" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r36">36</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig14.jpeg" height="868" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Right adnexal ectopic pregnancy in a 36-year-old woman who had undergone IVF. The patient presented with right lower quadrant pain, vaginal spotting, and a serum β-hCG level of 941 mIU/mL. Transverse transvaginal color Doppler US image of the right ovary <i>(OV)</i> shows an extraovarian adnexal mass (arrow) deep to and separate from the ovary. No color flow was detected, and the patient was treated with methotrexate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig15.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Tubal ring sign in ectopic pregnancy. Transvaginal US image of the right adnexa shows an echogenic ring surrounding an anechoic gestational sac <i>(GS)</i>. A cleavage plane (arrow) separates the gestational sac from the ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig16a.jpeg" height="825" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig16b.jpeg" height="817" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig17.jpeg" height="986" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Ectopic pregnancy in a 32-year-old woman who had undergone IVF. The patient presented with right pelvic pain and a serum β-hCG level of 850 mIU/mL. Axial T2-weighted MR image of the pelvis shows a 1.6-cm thick-walled cystic lesion (arrow) posterior to the right ovary, a finding that is suspicious for an ectopic pregnancy. Adjacent hematoma is also noted, a finding that is consistent with rupture. Right salpingectomy was performed, and findings at pathologic analysis confirmed a ruptured ectopic pregnancy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig18a.jpeg" height="851" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig18b.jpeg" height="836" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig18c.jpeg" height="898" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig19.jpeg" height="930" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Cervical ectopic pregnancy with a figure eight configuration of the uterus and cervix. On a US image, a gestational sac containing a yolk sac <i>(YS)</i> is seen in the cervix.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig20a.jpeg" height="926" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig20b.jpeg" height="906" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig21.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Cesarean scar ectopic pregnancy in a patient who was undergoing treatment for secondary infertility. Sagittal transvaginal US image shows a gestational sac with a fetal pole in the location of a prior cesarean scar in the lower uterine segment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig22a.jpeg" height="902" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig22b.jpeg" height="884" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig23a.jpeg" height="904" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig23b.jpeg" height="896" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig24a.jpeg" height="944" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig24b.jpeg" height="895" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig25a.jpeg" height="936" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.331125011/asset/images/125011fig25b.jpeg" height="932" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.331125011&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliogr